      "type": "add",
      "id": "3c6066179eb5e7b8",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "3c6066179eb5e7b8",
        "text": "Nicolas Schaller relates Spencer-Brown's discussion of the idea of an arithmetic of logic to Edmund Husserl's concept of number as an intentional act of a \"collective connection\" and Alexius Meinong's proposal that the concept of the object is not bound to its existence. This sheds light on Spencer-Brown's attempt to understand a distinction as an operation that follows laws that can be stated even when it is not bound by its object, but acts in a certain and not arbitrary freedom. Jean-Sébastien Guy concludes the mathematical round dance by placing Spencer-Brown's forms in relation to Felix Klein's geometry of invariance and interpreting both, as well as Niklas Luhmann's theorem of functional differentiation, as forms of modeling symmetry breaks. In mathematics as in sociology, this means that symmetry breaks can be understood as a form of the production of invariants, which in turn exhibit a multitude of transformations. Similar to geometry and the calculus of forms, invariants with many variants can also be identified in society, which can be traced back to certain laws of their transformation."
