      "type": "add",
      "id": "8eef7a7e6b3719ef",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "8eef7a7e6b3719ef",
        "text": "Franz Hoegl takes issue with attempts to understand Spencer-Brown's forms as \"formalisms\" in the context of sociological work with them and instead argues that they should be interpreted as \"symbolizing diagrams\". While he is thoroughly sceptical of the practice of entering terms or texts as \"variables\" in the forms, because strictly speaking the algebra of form works at best with parameters that in turn indicate marked or unmarked states, the work on form can at least be understood as a design practice that can illustrate forms of meaning that are not accessible to the senses objectively, temporally and socially - i.e. as a relation, as an event and for several viewers."
      },
      "after": "c773e1cbc4525fae",
      "date": 1701767956559
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "d41e11a1139bfe62",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "d41e11a1139bfe62",
        "text": "Dirk Baecker understands the Spencer-Brown transformation as a change from a philosophy, logic and sociology of identity to a philosophy, mathematics and sociology of difference. Every phenomenon a becomes determinable as a reflection on itself in the context of a reflection on what is included and excluded. In contrast to the Fourier transformation, which translates aperiodic signals into a continuous spectrum, the Spencer-Brown transformation consists of obtaining discrete signals or differences or forms from a continuous spectrum or medial substrate, whose operations in turn enrich the continuous spectrum. This can be followed by considerations on a general theory of digitization in social systems and with recourse to social networks. Thomas Götzelt draws on the Gilgameš epic to show social forms of the constitution of family, community and society, which not only stand in difference to each other, but also refer to a threatening and alluring third, the outside of their distinction (here Huwawa or the taboo), which gives their distinction a hold that is as secure as it is uncertain."
      },
      "after": "8eef7a7e6b3719ef",
      "date": 1701767974692
    },
