      "type": "add",
      "id": "dece9c7827c5181b",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "dece9c7827c5181b",
        "text": "Florian Grote uses the formal calculus to examine agile teams, which only find a form when they selectively distinguish roles and projects from one another and relate them to one another. His case study concerns student teams in the educational context of a university, whose discussions revolve around finding out which decisions are expected of them or are possible in their projects based on which decision-making premises. The teams only find a dynamically usable stability when they succeed in reliably distinguishing between decisions and decision premises in the meaning of an intrinsic form. Finally, Jan Tobias Fuhrmann takes a critical look at Luhmann's understanding of the two-sided form. The simultaneous observation of both sides, necessary for an understanding of their oscillation, is at best visually possible, while in communication it presupposes sustainability, i.e. sequentiality. With recourse to Jacques Derrida's concept of différance, the article advocates a distinction between violence and critique, insofar as critique is able to abolish the violence inherent in sequentiality. The two-sided form becomes violence when it does not allow for the leeway that the sustainability of the designation of the outside of a distinction inevitably possesses."
      },
      "after": "4043ff0909b4edd8",
      "date": 1701768004699
